  "prompt": "Where can I get a red coat, like Joaquin Phoenix used to wear in the movie Her, in India?",
  "response": "Finding a *perfect* replica of Theodore's red coat from \"Her\" might be tricky, but here's a breakdown of how you can find something similar in India:\n\n**1. Understand the Key Features:**\n\n*   **Color:**  A vibrant, somewhat muted, red (leaning towards brick red or burnt red).\n*   **Style:** A standing collar, often described as a Mao collar or mandarin collar. Minimalist design. Often made of wool.\n*   **Fit:** Relaxed and somewhat boxy.  Slightly oversized.\n*   **Closure:** Often a hidden button or snap closure.\n\n**2. Online Marketplaces (Best starting point):**\n\n*   **Amazon.in:** Search terms like: \"red standing collar coat men,\" \"red mandarin collar coat,\" \"red wool coat Indian style,\" \"Nehru collar red coat\", \"red overcoat men\"\n*   **Myntra:** Similar search terms as above. Myntra has a larger selection of brands.\n*   **Ajio:** Another good option for curated brands and wider styles.\n*   **Flipkart:** Less likely to have a *perfect* match, but still worth checking with the same search terms.\n*   **Nykaa Fashion:** Although more female-focused, they sometimes carry unisex or menswear-inspired pieces from various brands.\n*   **Etsy:**  Search for \"red mandarin collar coat\" or \"red Nehru collar coat\" with the location filter set to India (or worldwide, if you're willing to pay for international shipping). You might find handmade or vintage options.\n\n**3. Specialty Menswear Brands (Both Online & Offline):**\n\n*   **Raymond:**  Raymond is a well-known Indian tailoring and fabric brand.  You might be able to find a suitable fabric there and have a coat custom-made by their tailors. This would be the best option for an ideal fit.\n*   **Manyavar:** While Manyavar is known for ethnic wear, they *occasionally* carry modern-fusion pieces. Worth a look.\n*   **Peter England, Van Heusen, Allen Solly:** These mainstream brands may have red coats as part of their seasonal collections.\n\n**4. Tailoring Shops (Best for Customization):**\n\n*   **Local Tailors:** A good tailor can create a coat to your exact specifications.  Find a reputable tailor and show them pictures of Theodore's coat.  Source the fabric yourself (a good quality wool in the right shade of red).\n*   **Online Tailoring Services:** Some online services connect you with tailors for custom clothing. Check reviews and ensure they can handle the specific collar and style details.\n\n**5.  Specific Search Tips & Refinements:**\n\n*   **\"Nehru Collar\" or \"Mao Collar\":** Using these terms is crucial for finding the right collar style.\n*   **\"Wool Coat\":**  Will narrow the search for the right material.\n*   **\"Overcoat\":** This will help find longer coats suitable for layering.\n*   **Filter by Color:**  Most online stores allow you to filter by \"Red.\"\n*   **Check Size Charts:** Carefully review size charts, especially if ordering online, as sizing can vary between brands.\n*   **Read Reviews:** Reviews from other customers can provide valuable insights into the quality, fit, and color accuracy of the coat.\n\n**6. Fabric Considerations:**\n\n*   **Wool:**  Ideal for warmth and the closest to the look in the movie.\n*   **Wool Blend:** A more affordable option, but check the percentage of wool.\n*   **Cotton Blend:**  Can be a lighter-weight alternative, but less warm and may not drape as well.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Price:** Ready-made coats will range in price depending on the brand, materials, and quality. Custom-made coats will likely be more expensive, but you'll have complete control over the design.\n*   **Seasonality:** Red coats may be more readily available during the winter months.\n*   **Patience:**  Finding an *exact* match may take time and research.  Be prepared to browse extensively and compare options.  Consider settling for something \"inspired by\" Her, rather than an exact replica.\n*   **Photographs:** Take clear photos of the desired coat to show your tailor or when searching online. Angles from the front, side, and back are useful.\n*   **Material Sample:** If you want to get a custom-made coat, take a material sample to your tailor if you find fabric from somewhere else.\nGood luck with your search! Remember to prioritize quality, fit, and the overall aesthetic you're aiming for.\n",
